Executive Summary

Executives should focus on customer retention because customers seem to be price sensitive. Bringing highly engaged customers down from the \$90 to the \$70 monthly charge price point may increase retention. This can be achieved through a promotion, which we will A/B test. Increased customer lifetime value and decreased customer acquisition cost can offset the price of this promotion.

1.1 Quick Summary:

  • This data has extreme outliers, which is very common in tech. We can't just eliminate these outliers because they could be whale-customers, who should have their own metrics and their own strategy.

  • See above for percentiles. We will almost always speak in terms of percentiles so that we get a better idea of the data, not influenced by super-customers (outliers).

  • Note that, in the interest of time, I've simply dropped the NULLs, and cut out the false boolean 3 in the SeniorCitizen column. Usually, though, NULLs would get their own analysis just to make sure they are not systematically patterned.

  • Typically for product analysis, though not here due to exam time constraints, I'll focus on the Inter-Quartile Range to actually look at the relationship among and between features.

In [34]:
# you can bin with Pandas pd.cut 
# https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/reference/api/pandas.cut.html
ias_df_wrangled['monthlycharge_status'] = hds.pd.cut(ias_df_wrangled['MonthlyCharges'],
                                bins=[monthly_charges_min, monthly_charges_p33,
                                      monthly_charges_p66, monthly_charges_max],
                                labels=['low', 'medium', 'high'],
                                    include_lowest=True, right=True)  
# right means to include the rightmost bound in the to-the-left bin (inclusive) 
# include_lowest means to include the lowest_bound in the 'low category' (inclusive)

Question 2.2: Analyze the churn rate within each segment and provide insights

In [37]:
ias_q_2_2 = HaywardSQLAnalysis("ias")
ias_q_2_2.sendToSQL(ias_df_wrangled, "ias")
In [38]:
question2_part2 = ias_q_2_2.inlineSQL(f"""
SELECT
    monthlycharge_status as monthly_charge_status,
    churn as churn_status,
    count(distinct customerID) as customers,
    (
      1.0*count(distinct customerID)) 
        / 
    sum(count(distinct customerID)) over(partition by monthlycharge_status
    ) as percentage_per_monthly_charge_status
FROM ias
GROUP BY 1, 2
ORDER BY 
    CASE monthlycharge_status
        WHEN 'low' THEN 1
        WHEN 'medium' THEN 2
        WHEN 'high' THEN 3
        END
             ASC, --this is just so I produce the below just as I wnat to see it
             2
""")

                      y='percentage_per_monthly_charge_status', hue='churn_status',\
                      palette={'No': 'turquoise', 'Yes': 'salmon'})
PercentFormatter = hds.matplotlib.ticker.PercentFormatter
hds.plt.gca().yaxis.set_major_formatter(PercentFormatter(1))
hds.plt.title('Customer Churn Status by Monthly Charge Levels', fontweight="bold")
hds.plt.xlabel('Monthly Charge Status', fontweight="bold")
hds.plt.ylabel('Percentage', fontweight="bold")
hds.plt.legend(title='Churn Status')
hds.plt.show()
2.2 Quick Summary:

  • Here, we see better churn numbers for customers who have 'low' monthly charges.

  • It would seem that our ability to retain customers seems somehow tied to their price sensitivity. Unless the high-monthly-charge-paying customer is a totally different demographic with a different behavior, we might consider what types of promotions or cost reductions we can give them.

  • Even if a customer pays less up front (due to this promotion I hereby propose), if we retain them longer they can actually generate a higher lifetime value (LTV) for us, especially when we consider the costs of acquisition that we don't need to spend (or decreased cost, at least).

skew_kurt_df = hds.pd.DataFrame({
    'Category': ['Low', 'Medium', 'High'],
    'Skewness': [
        hds.skew(low_cust['MonthlyCharges']),
        hds.skew(medium_cust['MonthlyCharges']),
        hds.skew(high_cust['MonthlyCharges'])
    ],
    'Kurtosis': [
        hds.kurtosis(low_cust['MonthlyCharges']),
        hds.kurtosis(medium_cust['MonthlyCharges']),
        hds.kurtosis(high_cust['MonthlyCharges'])
    ]
})

# melting will help us with the hews
skew_kurt_melted = skew_kurt_df.melt(id_vars='Category', var_name='Stat', value_name='Value')

hds.plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
hds.sns.barplot(data=skew_kurt_melted, x='Category', y='Value', hue='Stat', palette=['#1aa7ec', '#ffb347'])
hds.plt.axhline(0, color='gray', linewidth=0.8)  # Adding a line at y=0 for reference
hds.plt.title('Skewness and Kurtosis by Customer Monthly Charge Status', fontweight='bold')
hds.plt.ylabel('Unitless Numbers', fontweight='bold')
hds.plt.xlabel('Monthly Charge Category', fontweight='bold')
hds.plt.show()
""" Kurtosis Definition: Kurtosis measures the tailedness of a distribution. A high kurtosis (kurtosis > 3, leptokurtic) means that data are heavy-tailed or have outliers. A low kurtosis (kurtosis < 3, platykurtic) indicates light tails or a lack of outliers in a distribution. A kurtosis of about 3 (mesokurtic) resembles a normal distribution. """""" Skewness Definition: Skewness measures the asymmetry of a distribution around its mean. Positive skew (skewness > 0) indicates a distribution with a tail extending towards higher values; negative skew (skewness < 0) has a tail extending towards lower values. """
2.4 Quick Summary:

  • Across all categories, we see low and negative kurtosis, which means the herd is bunched together, generally, and we don't see too many outliers.

  • Skewness is about which side the tail of the distribution extends outward. When skew is positive, it means samples are bunching lower because the long-tail extends to the right, and when skew is negative samples are bunching higher, because there the long tail extends to the left. The high customers seem to bunch around \$90 (which is actually lower for their band, and that's a reason I propose a promotion towards the higher-end customers), medium customers seem to bunch around \$75, and low customers seem to bunch around \$20 a month.

  • Given what we know about churn, I would want to see how we could move some of those 'high' customers in the \$90 range over to the \$75 range, where we seem to have much better retention.

  • With more time, I'd think about a lifetime value sensitivity analysis because there must be a promotion where the lower monthly charge is evened out by the extended lifetime value gained. We'd want to figure out which customers would be most amenable to said promotion (we will know this from their engagement metrics), and then offer them that discount.

3.1 Quick Summary:

  • XGBoost splits all features along places where it follows a loss function to lower the Gini coefficient for various features (how purely feature split can separate the win-case from the loss-case of the dependent variable, which, here, is "Churn"), so it's very robust for these types of analyses, where we are not sure if something is even linear and we have a lot of colinearity.

  • In terms of model stats, I'm very happy with the first run. Accuracy of 78% is way better than a coin flip, so it makes us think that the model "knows something."

  • Precision basically means, if I call it an X, is it an X. Here, we're pretty good, though we can be better.

  • Recall basically means, of all the X's out there, how many did I catch. Here, again, we're pretty good.

  • F1 score is a combination of the two, and F1 is harder to interpret, so you use it relatively, and I like what I see here.

  • The ROC_AUC is a favorite metric of data scientists, and I like to think of it as the one-number to assess the model. Here 70%, is way better than a coin flip (which would be 50%), so I'm happy.

  • Remember, this is with no feature engineering other than handling categoricals, so we definitely have signal in this data. A great feeling :).

  • For the next feature selection problem, I'll do a backwards elimination regression.

F1: 0.5795454545454546

3.2 Quick Summary:

  • This is a time-limited exam, so I won't go further, but you see the point: we often want to get the model down to just a handful of features that an executive can quickly comprehend and hold in his/her/their mind.

  • Additionally, there are other ways to feature prune. I can do it on correlation scores, though generally, I like to use a gradient boosted tree, which does not mind colinearity as much as a logistic regression will.

  • I like this pruning technique because when we look at p-values and coefficients as a way to prune, it's a way for to take into account one variable's lift considering all the other inter-related and inter-acting variables, so this p-value/coefficient method (here I use the lowest absolute coefficient to 'the next feature off the island,' so to speak), lets us to whittle down the model without losing the big picture.

  • Logistic regressions are a bit more interpretable than XGBoost, which can be a bit of a black box. So when whittling down the features, it helps to see the impact of each one as we go. Now it is possible to get an idea of XGBoost with SHAP values, but that's outside the scope for now. When showing an executive, a logistic regression is best, I think, and when modeling a XGBoost model has more power, though we lose some interpretability.

  • We also do want to apply common sense. A one year contract, and a two year contract are bins for tenure, so we may consider some of those features 'cheating,' and we'd remove them to better understand the data.

  • In practice I prefer to run models such as this on the IQR (interquartile range), unless we are dealing with data that relies heavily on the impact of outliers, such as insurance datasets.

  • As you can see above with my dotted black horizontal line at \$70, most of the churns happen with the higher prices, and earlier on in tenure. I recommend offering customers a sale or promotion at some point in their first 10 months to get them as close to \$70 a month as possible. Once this sale/promotion launches, we will A/B test the customer retention, and if we see a true effect (or at least a strong correlation) from the sale/promotion, we will then adjust down the dollar amount of the sale/promotion to match the business break even point. Meaning: we'll adjust this promotion/sale offering to a price level so that the money we lose in the month-to-month charges, we ultimately get recoup in the lifetime value of the customer that we didn't lose, and in savings from the customer acquisition costs we no longer have.
